00:00:21.710 --> 00:00:24.080
What Is Knowledge?

00:00:24.080 --> 00:00:29.080
What do I know, is the
topic for this evening.

00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:34.520
This is our penultimate
session of 10 Questions.

00:00:36.100 --> 00:00:37.420
And one of our guests this evening

00:00:37.420 --> 00:00:39.820
asked if I could work the
word penultimate in early,

00:00:39.820 --> 00:00:41.723
so, check, done.

00:00:43.130 --> 00:00:46.053
How do we know what penultimate means?

00:00:48.810 --> 00:00:50.940
Most of us know what the word means

00:00:50.940 --> 00:00:54.070
but we don't know
exactly how we know that.

00:00:54.070 --> 00:00:55.670
We just do.

00:00:55.670 --> 00:00:58.490
And with that I introduce tonight's topic

00:00:58.490 --> 00:01:03.030
which is to stand back
from our daily lives

00:01:03.030 --> 00:01:07.740
organized around the
acquisition of, presentation of,

00:01:09.180 --> 00:01:12.780
conservation of knowledge
of various kinds.

00:01:12.780 --> 00:01:14.680
And I'm thinking
especially of you students

00:01:14.680 --> 00:01:18.350
who will be tested on knowledge
in a couple of weeks time

00:01:18.350 --> 00:01:20.300
in various classes.

00:01:20.300 --> 00:01:23.360
To think instead about
the larger topic or idea,

00:01:23.360 --> 00:01:28.360
this very, very special, very
human, almost incomparable

00:01:28.510 --> 00:01:31.830
concept that we have of
knowledge in the world

00:01:31.830 --> 00:01:36.050
and how that concept
relates to or differs from

00:01:36.050 --> 00:01:40.330
things very close to it,
like ideas, like information,

00:01:40.330 --> 00:01:44.300
like many other things that
seems to sit closely aside

00:01:44.300 --> 00:01:48.950
this very human quality and concept.

00:01:48.950 --> 00:01:51.100
To ask, what is knowledge,

00:01:51.100 --> 00:01:52.750
I think if we think about it for a minute

00:01:52.750 --> 00:01:57.750
is very abstract, almost obscure or obtuse

00:01:58.230 --> 00:02:00.290
compared to some of the
questions we've asked

00:02:00.290 --> 00:02:01.710
over the last couple of months.

00:02:01.710 --> 00:02:06.533
If you think of beauty, failure, time,

00:02:07.378 --> 00:02:11.560
big, human or at times
intensely personal ideas.

00:02:11.560 --> 00:02:14.070
To ask, what is knowledge, you gotta admit

00:02:14.070 --> 00:02:16.493
sounds a little bit know-it-all-like.

00:02:17.610 --> 00:02:21.513
And a very UCLA kinda thing, right?

00:02:22.480 --> 00:02:26.180
It is, however, by design, a
question that's gonna lead us

00:02:26.180 --> 00:02:27.820
into the final one of this series

00:02:27.820 --> 00:02:32.090
which is to contemplate:
What is a University?

00:02:32.090 --> 00:02:34.270
And we're joined by some
terrific guests this evening

00:02:34.270 --> 00:02:36.950
who are gonna help us with that work.

00:02:36.950 --> 00:02:40.780
I'm old enough, I think,
to be comfortable in saying

00:02:40.780 --> 00:02:45.753
I feel like I know what I know
and I know what I don't know.

00:02:46.650 --> 00:02:48.953
One of the incredible
pleasures of being a dean

00:02:48.953 --> 00:02:51.550
at a school like the School
of the Arts and Architecture

00:02:51.550 --> 00:02:55.620
at UCLA is I spend my
days literally with people

00:02:55.620 --> 00:02:57.563
who know way more than I do.

00:02:58.830 --> 00:03:00.340
Including you students, I promise,

00:03:00.340 --> 00:03:02.080
you know things that most of us at my age

00:03:02.080 --> 00:03:05.163
can't even imagine let alone comprehend.

00:03:06.330 --> 00:03:07.868
But all of this focus on
though, in our daily lives

00:03:07.868 --> 00:03:10.710
as we contemplate that kind of reality

00:03:10.710 --> 00:03:13.250
is, of course, who it is we might turn to

00:03:13.250 --> 00:03:14.930
how it is we might think

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:19.170
how it is we relay that
thing we treat as knowledge.

00:03:19.170 --> 00:03:23.760
And tonight's work is gonna
continue that sort of thinking.

00:03:23.760 --> 00:03:25.890
That said, for me, there are three things

00:03:25.890 --> 00:03:27.523
I do know about knowledge.

00:03:28.400 --> 00:03:31.580
The first is, it's incredibly valuable

00:03:31.580 --> 00:03:34.490
and arguably more valuable than ever

00:03:35.560 --> 00:03:38.522
at a time described in relation to

00:03:38.522 --> 00:03:41.523
an idea like knowledge economies.

00:03:42.620 --> 00:03:44.540
That suddenly place more value

00:03:44.540 --> 00:03:48.270
in literal monetary terms on ideas

00:03:48.270 --> 00:03:50.250
than it often will on hard stuff

00:03:50.250 --> 00:03:54.470
like bricks and mortar, glass or steel.

00:03:54.470 --> 00:03:58.633
The second thing I know is
that knowledge is vulnerable.

00:04:00.150 --> 00:04:04.080
Particularly, you could
say, in an era of fake news

00:04:05.260 --> 00:04:09.123
or rampant conspiracy theory industries.

00:04:10.130 --> 00:04:12.240
Whatever it is, is
something that we all need

00:04:12.240 --> 00:04:16.080
to think carefully about
protecting and not just conserving.

00:04:16.080 --> 00:04:18.023
And finally, knowledge is endurable.

00:04:19.995 --> 00:04:22.710
It is enduring, and an enduring feature

00:04:22.710 --> 00:04:26.610
of who and what we are as a species.

00:04:26.610 --> 00:04:29.910
Whatever else it is, knowledge
is something we humans

00:04:29.910 --> 00:04:34.620
produce and value, it's
something we share,

00:04:34.620 --> 00:04:37.543
we broadcast, we socialize.

00:04:38.560 --> 00:04:43.560
We occasionally monetize
or even monopolize

00:04:43.620 --> 00:04:47.510
in spectacular and unexpected ways.

00:04:47.510 --> 00:04:49.870
A final way in which we might
think about the importance

00:04:49.870 --> 00:04:53.873
of asking questions about
what is knowledge today.

00:04:54.840 --> 00:04:58.300
So with that, as something less

00:04:58.300 --> 00:05:00.970
