Your eyes are open.

00:15:05.100 --> 00:15:06.873
You're breathing quietly.

00:15:07.790 --> 00:15:09.530
If you've got your computer open,

00:15:09.530 --> 00:15:11.593
you're probably taking notes.

00:15:13.700 --> 00:15:16.020
So, I think that that demonstrates

00:15:16.020 --> 00:15:17.500
that we have a shared knowledge

00:15:17.500 --> 00:15:20.950
about what's appropriate
for being in a lecture.

00:15:20.950 --> 00:15:23.370
But just to take that a step further

00:15:24.266 --> 00:15:27.116
first of all, I'd like to,
can anybody whistle like this?

00:15:28.429 --> 00:15:29.720
(person whistles)

00:15:29.720 --> 00:15:31.198
Okay, thank you.

00:15:31.198 --> 00:15:32.210
(audience laughs)

00:15:32.210 --> 00:15:34.330
The next time you hear that whistle,

00:15:34.330 --> 00:15:39.060
I'd like to invite
everyone here to misbehave.

00:15:39.060 --> 00:15:42.100
Now, just a couple of rules.

00:15:42.100 --> 00:15:44.730
Don't hurt yourself, don't
hurt the person next to you

00:15:44.730 --> 00:15:46.923
and please don't wreck the property.

00:15:48.620 --> 00:15:50.340
You have 10 seconds to misbehave.

00:15:50.340 --> 00:15:51.910
When you hear the whistle the second time

00:15:51.910 --> 00:15:54.713
please, please stop, okay?

00:15:55.649 --> 00:15:57.023
All right, ready?

00:15:59.378 --> 00:16:01.056
(person whistles)

00:16:01.056 --> 00:16:03.329
(audience clamors)

00:16:03.329 --> 00:16:06.162
(audience laughs)

00:16:10.060 --> 00:16:10.893
And.

00:16:12.243 --> 00:16:14.370
(person whistles)

00:16:14.370 --> 00:16:16.530
Thank you very much.

00:16:16.530 --> 00:16:18.640
So you know what misbehavior is,

00:16:18.640 --> 00:16:21.770
proving what the appropriate behavior is.

00:16:21.770 --> 00:16:23.870
And for those of you who refused my offer,

00:16:23.870 --> 00:16:25.943
was there anyone who refused my offer?

00:16:27.380 --> 00:16:29.930
Okay, well I can think of two things.

00:16:29.930 --> 00:16:34.930
Either you have so absorbed
the authoritative requirements

00:16:36.270 --> 00:16:37.310
for being in a lecture,

00:16:37.310 --> 00:16:41.340
maybe you felt that you
couldn't really misbehave.

00:16:41.340 --> 00:16:44.270
Or, and I bet it's the second.

00:16:44.270 --> 00:16:48.760
You were asked to transgress,
and you thought to yourself,

00:16:48.760 --> 00:16:50.700
oh, the authoritative voice in the room

00:16:50.700 --> 00:16:52.650
is asking me to transgress,

00:16:52.650 --> 00:16:56.470
and so, if I transgress
that is not transgressing

00:16:56.470 --> 00:16:58.930
and therefore if I sit still
(audience laughs)

00:16:58.930 --> 00:17:03.210
and I don't transgress, then
I will be really thwarting

00:17:03.210 --> 00:17:04.740
the appropriate behavior in the room.

00:17:04.740 --> 00:17:07.087
I see you nodding your
heads yes, so now I know.

00:17:07.087 --> 00:17:09.920
(audience laughs)

00:17:10.990 --> 00:17:12.603
Here's my next act.

00:17:14.550 --> 00:17:17.793
We elevate some kinds of
knowledge and dismiss others.

00:17:20.660 --> 00:17:22.200
Okay.

00:17:22.200 --> 00:17:26.930
Consider the many everyday
techniques you know

00:17:26.930 --> 00:17:28.870
and let's, for example,

00:17:28.870 --> 00:17:30.480
think about the technique of driving.

00:17:30.480 --> 00:17:31.703
How many of you drive?

00:17:32.730 --> 00:17:33.563
Okay, good.

00:17:33.563 --> 00:17:37.120
And we know that, uh oh. (blowing)

00:17:37.120 --> 00:17:39.710
We know that you drive (laughing)

00:17:39.710 --> 00:17:42.480
okay, listen, we know that
you drive very, very well

00:17:42.480 --> 00:17:44.563
because you're here.

00:17:46.610 --> 00:17:49.630
And how many of you,
I mean, oh, nevermind.

00:17:49.630 --> 00:17:50.870
I'm not gonna ask for numbers.

00:17:50.870 --> 00:17:55.140
But also, most of us know
the appropriate comportment

00:17:55.140 --> 00:17:58.210
and etiquette for eating, is that correct?

00:17:58.210 --> 00:18:00.900
Good, so we can have dinner together.

00:18:00.900 --> 00:18:04.520
But basically, these are techniques.

00:18:04.520 --> 00:18:08.970
They are techniques
which you have perfected

00:18:08.970 --> 00:18:12.130
or quickly, hopefully, will soon perfect

00:18:12.130 --> 00:18:14.140
your skills in these areas.

00:18:14.140 --> 00:18:17.140
And you do that through repetition.

00:18:17.140 --> 00:18:20.280
You just do it over
and over and over again

00:18:20.280 --> 00:18:23.973
until it begins to feel natural.

00:18:25.620 --> 00:18:28.040
So nothing actually is natural,

00:18:28.040 --> 00:18:30.930
but we have the experience of something

00:18:30.930 --> 00:18:33.470
we've learned as being natural

00:18:33.470 --> 00:18:37.230
when we have repeated it so often

00:18:37.230 --> 00:18:39.240
that we no longer have to bring

00:18:39.240 --> 00:18:42.720
an attenuated focus to every next move.

00:18:42.720 --> 00:18:44.943
We have absorbed that knowledge.

00:18:48.010 --> 00:18:49.210
As long as that's clear.

00:18:50.780 --> 00:18:55.240
When you do a headstand, by
the way, I can do a headstand

00:18:55.240 --> 00:18:58.890
but I'm just a little
nervous to do it right now.

00:18:58.890 --> 00:19:00.339
(audience laughs)

00:19:00.339 --> 00:19:04.760
But when you do a headstand
at a club or at a party

00:19:04.760 --> 00:19:07.760
or maybe like in a lecture hall.

00:19:07.760 --> 00:19:09.703
Or at home in your living room.

00:19:10.980 --> 00:19:13.270
You are displaying technique.

00:19:13.270 --> 00:19:17.280
And you are demonstrating
a set of skills, knowledge.

00:19:17.280 --> 00:19:19.190
And when you are really, really good,

00:19:19.190 --> 00:19:21.330
you're able to generate new ideas

00:19:21.330 --> 00:19:23.530
within your headstanding technique.

00:19:23.530 --> 00:19:25.980
And I'll just let you
imagine what that could be.

00:19:27.280 --> 00:19:29.680
All dancers study technique,

00:19:29.680 --> 00:19:31.930
whether in the studio or on the street.

00:19:31.930 --> 00:19:33.560
And mastery of technique

00:19:33.560 --> 00:19:36.563
allows for freedom within that technique.

00:19:37.870 --> 00:19:40.360
But what I want to say here is technique

00:19:40.360 --> 00:19:43.210
is not about learning movement alone.

00:19:43.210 --> 00:19:44.500
Not at all.

00:19:44.500 --> 00:19:46.610
When you practice a technique,

00:19:46.610 --> 00:19:49.690
whether dancing or eating dinner,

00:19:49.690 --> 00:19:52.530
or driving your car, or washing,

00:19:52.530 --> 00:19:56.000
you enact a set of beliefs and values.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:58.920
All techniques are philosophical practices

00:19:58.920 --> 00:20:03.433
that locate personhood and
also collective beliefs.

00:20:04.280 --> 00:20:07.533
Each technique puts us in
the world in its own way.

00:20:10.440 --> 00:20:13.803
Dancing is ephemeral.

00:20:15.060 --> 00:20:16.053
Like life.

00:20:18.970 --> 00:20:21.343
It leaves no tangible trace.

00:20:22.650 --> 00:20:25.173
It's here and gone.

00:20:26.870 --> 00:20:31.560
And when dancers work, their
labor leaves no object,

00:20:31.560 --> 00:20:34.513
no commodity that can be owned or sold.

00:20:35.360 --> 00:20:40.360
Only, as in life, a visceral
memory of lives fully lived

00:20:41.250 --> 00:20:43.993
precariously and with great love.

00:20:46.860 --> 00:20:51.860
If we view our bodies as things,
as objects to be studied,

00:20:52.710 --> 00:20:56.090
controlled and subdued, then by extension,

00:20:56.090 --> 00:20:57.760
we have a template through which

00:20:57.760 --> 00:21:00.223
to objectify and control others.

00:21:01.090 --> 00:21:04.890
We're accustomed to thinking of power,

00:21:04.890 --> 00:21:07.750
the dominion of some
people over other people,

00:21:07.750 --> 00:21:10.800
some communities over other communities,

00:21:10.800 --> 00:21:13.240
nations over nations,

00:21:13.240 --> 00:21:18.130
humans over animals,
humans over the earth.

00:21:18.130 --> 00:21:22.340
And when we, in the hubris
of our own elevated status

00:21:22.340 --> 00:21:25.820
look down at animals or other people

00:21:25.820 --> 00:21:29.300
this reductive act diminishes knowledge

00:21:29.300 --> 00:21:32.370
and then we call it instinct.

00:21:32.370 --> 00:21:34.693
And that enables us to kill.

00:21:36.830 --> 00:21:38.750
When we attempt to control the body,

00:21:38.750 --> 00:21:42.550
to treat the body as an
object that we subdue,

00:21:42.550 --> 00:21:46.440
which may be in part
necessary for our survival,

00:21:46.440 --> 00:21:48.130
that same act of control

00:21:48.130 --> 00:21:51.143
can be a form of assault
on knowledge itself.

00:21:52.290 --> 00:21:55.800
What if instead of positioning knowledge

00:21:55.800 --> 00:21:57.760
solely as an act of the mind

00:21:57.760 --> 00:22:00.260
a state of dominion over the body,

00:22:00.260 --> 00:22:03.800
we considered the body
as a source of knowledge

00:22:03.800 --> 00:22:05.363
and a way of knowing?

00:22:06.410 --> 00:22:07.503
Thank you.

00:22:07.503 --> 00:22:08.450
(audience applauds)

00:22:08.450 --> 00:22:09.983
- Thank you, Victoria.

00:22:12.082 --> 00:22:14.373
Thank you so much, thank you.

00:22:14.373 --> 00:22:16.240
Everybody, Todd Presner.

00:22:17.116 --> 00:22:19.323
- I'm gonna grab the clicker.

00:22:24.500 --> 00:22:26.000
Thank you so much.

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.800
It's really a pleasure
to be able to participate

00:22:28.800 --> 00:22:30.870
in this experiment with you all.

00:22:30.870 --> 00:22:34.710
And thank you Victoria and
Brett, and my colleagues

00:22:34.710 --> 00:22:38.320
for allowing me to be here
and share some thoughts.

00:22:38.320 --> 00:22:41.630
When I think about the
question, what is knowledge,

00:22:41.630 --> 00:22:44.230
immediately I begin to proliferate

00:22:44.230 --> 00:22:45.960
a whole set of other questions.

00:22:45.960 --> 00:22:47.640
Whose knowledge are we talking about?

00:22:47.640 --> 00:22:49.940
Where is this knowledge,
where do we find it?

00:22:49.940 --> 00:22:52.200
How did it become knowledge
in the first place?

00:22:52.200 --> 00:22:53.500
Who's credentialed it?

00:22:53.500 --> 00:22:56.470
Who certified that that's
knowledge there, that's not?

00:22:56.470 --> 00:22:57.400
Why this knowledge

00:22:57.400 --> 00:22:59.830
as opposed to some
other kind of knowledge?

00:22:59.830 --> 00:23:02.030
And, as someone that
works in the field of,

00:23:02.030 --> 00:23:04.230
imagine you heard a little bit,

00:23:04.230 --> 00:23:07.090
digital humanities is one
thing I do, I work with media,

00:23:07.090 --> 00:23:08.400
but I'm also a historian.

00:23:08.400 --> 00:23:11.830
I work particularly on German
and German-Jewish history

00:23:11.830 --> 00:23:13.290
and I'll get to that in a moment.

00:23:13.290 --> 00:23:16.170
But I also think about
knowledge that's varied

00:23:16.170 --> 00:23:18.140
and silenced or submerged.

00:23:18.140 --> 00:23:22.780
And I wonder a lot about
knowledge that becomes lost

00:23:22.780 --> 00:23:25.700
and what it means to find
that knowledge, to excavate it

00:23:25.700 --> 00:23:27.970
and particularly when it comes to voices

00:23:27.970 --> 00:23:30.570
that have been erased or obliterated

00:23:30.570 --> 00:23:32.100
from the cultural record.

00:23:32.100 --> 00:23:34.620
That, to me, becomes a
politics of knowledge

00:23:34.620 --> 00:23:38.850
and really, in some ways, lays
forward the ethical stakes

00:23:38.850 --> 00:23:42.083
of the entire enterprise of
what we do at a university.

00:23:43.810 --> 00:23:44.643
Where is knowledge?

00:23:44.643 --> 00:23:46.870
Well, oftentimes we think
of things like this.

00:23:46.870 --> 00:23:49.720
Grandiose spaces, the Library of Congress,

00:23:49.720 --> 00:23:53.630
beautiful, masterful,
architectural, ornate.

00:23:53.630 --> 00:23:56.370
Reading rooms and then the
storehouses of knowledge

00:23:56.370 --> 00:24:00.290
in stacks in libraries, and
they're organized in nice boxes.

00:24:00.290 --> 00:24:02.530
They're cataloged and they're
organized and classified

00:24:02.530 --> 00:24:05.240
because knowledge is always
organized and classified.

00:24:05.240 --> 00:24:08.260
And in so far as we think
about classification systems

00:24:08.260 --> 00:24:10.610
we realize those too are political.

00:24:10.610 --> 00:24:13.450
Well, if we go to the history
of even the word archive

00:24:13.450 --> 00:24:15.870
we already connect it with power.

00:24:15.870 --> 00:24:17.790
It comes from the Greek term archeion.

00:24:17.790 --> 00:24:19.940
It means a house or a domicile,

00:24:19.940 --> 00:24:22.280
but not just any domicile
or anyone's house,

00:24:22.280 --> 00:24:25.210
but the domicile of the
superior magistrates

00:24:25.210 --> 00:24:27.800
who are the archeions, those who command.

00:24:27.800 --> 00:24:30.840
And so knowledge is
something that's guarded.

00:24:30.840 --> 00:24:33.700
Some people have access to
it, can get into the archive,

00:24:33.700 --> 00:24:34.910
other people do not.

00:24:34.910 --> 00:24:36.210
And that already tells me

00:24:36.210 --> 00:24:37.950
that we have to think about the nexus

00:24:37.950 --> 00:24:41.160
between knowledge and
power from the get-go.

00:24:41.160 --> 00:24:44.850
The Mercator projection,
1596, an amazing feat.

00:24:44.850 --> 00:24:46.280
Google maps uses it today

00:24:46.280 --> 00:24:48.120
because it's useful for navigation.

00:24:48.120 --> 00:24:51.080
It doesn't distort in
the way other maps do.

00:24:51.080 --> 00:24:55.330
Very useful for ship
trade, ship navigation.

00:24:55.330 --> 00:24:57.600
Slave trade as well.

00:24:57.600 --> 00:25:00.080
Printing press, of course, it disseminates

00:25:00.080 --> 00:25:01.030
knowledge to the world.

00:25:01.030 --> 00:25:03.480
But of course, it creates
a public that can read

00:25:03.480 --> 00:25:05.780
and another public that
maybe is illiterate.

00:25:05.780 --> 00:25:08.590
We think of the scribal
tradition of writing down text

00:25:08.590 --> 00:25:09.790
of translating them.

00:25:09.790 --> 00:25:12.240
Who's overseeing them,
what texts get translated,

00:25:12.240 --> 00:25:13.540
what texts get lost?

00:25:13.540 --> 00:25:17.090
Or the idea of codification
of knowledge into great books.

00:25:17.090 --> 00:25:18.370
Philosophical tradition.

00:25:18.370 --> 00:25:20.330
I read these great books
when I was in college

00:25:20.330 --> 00:25:21.790
and I was like, oh, these
are the great books.

00:25:21.790 --> 00:25:23.350
This is knowledge, it's right there.

00:25:23.350 --> 00:25:24.183
(audience laughs)

00:25:24.183 --> 00:25:26.803
As it turns out, it's a really
small fraction of knowledge.

00:25:28.700 --> 00:25:30.620
So, I always have to think about,

00:25:30.620 --> 00:25:34.430
knowledge is not just about
power, it's also empowerment.

00:25:34.430 --> 00:25:37.210
Because we have the ability to speak back.

00:25:38.218 --> 00:25:39.850
And you have to ask the
question, who can speak?

00:25:39.850 --> 00:25:41.510
In what languages, in what media?

00:25:41.510 --> 00:25:43.640
How are they credentialed, by whom?

00:25:43.640 --> 00:25:45.310
What institutions and communities

00:25:45.310 --> 00:25:47.890
are involved in organizing
and preserving knowledge?

00:25:47.890 --> 00:25:49.640
And especially in so far as

00:25:49.640 --> 00:25:51.990
we think about applications of knowledge,

00:25:51.990 --> 00:25:53.660
how does knowledge lead to action?

00:25:53.660 --> 00:25:55.020
What does it mean that we know something?

00:25:55.020 --> 00:25:56.200
Do we actually act on it?

00:25:56.200 --> 00:25:58.200
Do we do something about it?

00:25:58.200 --> 00:26:00.850
Amazing exhibition right now
by Adrian Piper at the Hammer

00:26:00.850 --> 00:26:03.330
that deals with exactly this issue.

00:26:03.330 --> 00:26:05.510
I work in the field of
Holocaust and genocide studies.

00:26:05.510 --> 00:26:08.010
This, obviously, it's
a deep, difficult field

00:26:08.010 --> 00:26:09.190
in a lot of ways.

00:26:09.190 --> 00:26:12.620
But genocide, the term genocide
means the killing of a race.

00:26:12.620 --> 00:26:14.750
In German, they use the term
(speaking in foreign language)

00:26:14.750 --> 00:26:16.370
which means annihilation.

00:26:16.370 --> 00:26:18.360
To refer to what the Nazis were gonna do

00:26:18.360 --> 00:26:21.260
not just to the Jews, but
especially Jews and other groups

00:26:21.260 --> 00:26:23.870
that they considered to be sub-human.

00:26:23.870 --> 00:26:26.090
It's not only about the
destruction of a people.

00:26:26.090 --> 00:26:28.120
It's also the destruction of knowledge.

00:26:28.120 --> 00:26:29.400
It's a destruction of culture.

00:26:29.400 --> 00:26:31.140
It's a destruction of society.

00:26:31.140 --> 00:26:33.600
It's the destruction of
the historical record

00:26:33.600 --> 00:26:35.320
and that's really what's at stake

00:26:35.320 --> 00:26:38.713
when we begin to think about
power and power over others.

00:26:40.020 --> 00:26:42.710
Hannah Arendt's a great
German-Jewish philosopher

00:26:42.710 --> 00:26:44.440
who herself escaped Nazi Germany

00:26:44.440 --> 00:26:48.360
wrote about the origins of
totalitarianism in 1951.

00:26:48.360 --> 00:26:50.800
About fascism, about Stalinism.

00:26:50.800 --> 00:26:52.690
She says, the goal of totalitarianism

00:26:52.690 --> 00:26:55.550
is to see that the victim
never existed at all.

00:26:55.550 --> 00:26:58.330
And very hauntingly
quotes a survivor who says

00:26:58.330 --> 00:27:01.710
when no witnesses are left,
there can be no testimony.

00:27:01.710 --> 00:27:04.360
Well, witness means to know.

00:27:04.360 --> 00:27:07.260
Someone who witnesses things, knows them.

00:27:07.260 --> 00:27:10.060
He or she experienced something.

00:27:10.060 --> 00:27:12.440
It's not just ocular,
not just that you saw it,

00:27:12.440 --> 00:27:13.710
but that you experienced it.

00:27:13.710 --> 00:27:15.150
You went through something.

00:27:15.150 --> 00:27:18.290
And to testify is to
bring knowledge to others.

00:27:18.290 --> 00:27:21.030
It's to attest, it's to bear witness,

00:27:21.030 --> 00:27:22.500
it's to provide evidence and proof.

00:27:22.500 --> 00:27:23.890
I saw this, this happened,

00:27:23.890 --> 00:27:26.833
I was there and this is what happened.

00:27:27.970 --> 00:27:31.820
So to destroy those things
is to destroy knowledge.

00:27:31.820 --> 00:27:35.760
This is the last months of the liquidation

00:27:35.760 --> 00:27:37.490
of the Warsaw ghetto in 1943,

00:27:37.490 --> 00:27:39.900
before these people were
shipped out to Treblinka

00:27:39.900 --> 00:27:42.800
where they're almost all gassed.

00:27:42.800 --> 00:27:46.770
In the archive that was
created in the Warsaw ghetto

00:27:46.770 --> 00:27:49.810
a man named Emanuel
Ringelblum, a historian,

00:27:49.810 --> 00:27:51.590
decided to collect documents

00:27:51.590 --> 00:27:53.410
of what people were experiencing

00:27:53.410 --> 00:27:57.110
in these horrific years of 1941, '42, '43.

00:27:57.110 --> 00:27:59.667
And he decided to know
about everyday life.

00:27:59.667 --> 00:28:01.980
What were people experiencing?

00:28:01.980 --> 00:28:04.150
He wrote, not a single
fact should be omitted.

00:28:04.150 --> 00:28:07.570
Let the world read and know
what the murderers have done.

00:28:07.570 --> 00:28:08.660
What did they do with the archive?

00:28:08.660 --> 00:28:09.770
They buried it.

00:28:09.770 --> 00:28:11.670
They buried it in the ground,

00:28:11.670 --> 00:28:14.010
deep in the ground in metal boxes.

00:28:14.010 --> 00:28:16.180
After the war, three people survived

00:28:16.180 --> 00:28:18.030
who know about where this archive was.

00:28:18.030 --> 00:28:20.660
They dug it up in 1946 and 1951.

00:28:20.660 --> 00:28:23.690
Only parts of it, part of it's been lost.

00:28:23.690 --> 00:28:26.360
It was in milk crates,
it was in metal boxes.

00:28:26.360 --> 00:28:28.970
And what was inside were
testimonies of people

00:28:28.970 --> 00:28:30.550
who were themselves killed.

00:28:30.550 --> 00:28:31.550
These were their last words.

00:28:31.550 --> 00:28:33.840
These were wills, these were
letters, these were sermons,

00:28:33.840 --> 00:28:35.790
these were newspaper clippings,

00:28:35.790 --> 00:28:38.250
they were reports in multiple languages.

00:28:38.250 --> 00:28:41.453
But it was knowledge meant
to be shipped to the future.

00:28:42.670 --> 00:28:44.750
Shipped out of the Warsaw ghetto.

00:28:44.750 --> 00:28:47.870
And it was so precarious
because what's the chances

00:28:47.870 --> 00:28:50.960
that anyone would survive to
actually know where it was

00:28:50.960 --> 00:28:53.810
to dig it up and then to
recognize it as knowledge

00:28:53.810 --> 00:28:56.310
and say, this is important,
it's worth preserving.

00:28:57.420 --> 00:28:58.840
I've been interested in this concept

00:28:58.840 --> 00:29:01.820
of sending messages to the
future for a long time.

00:29:01.820 --> 00:29:03.330
And I'm particularly struck by the idea

00:29:03.330 --> 00:29:04.940
of putting a message in a bottle.

00:29:04.940 --> 00:29:06.750
Like, why would you put
a message in a bottle?

00:29:06.750 --> 00:29:08.010
Like, where are you sending it to,

00:29:08.010 --> 00:29:10.880
especially if you don't know
you're ever gonna survive?

00:29:10.880 --> 00:29:13.730
A woman from Ravensbruck, a
women's concentration camp

00:29:13.730 --> 00:29:15.810
who made art and buried it in a bottle

00:29:15.810 --> 00:29:18.250
that was only dug up years later.

00:29:18.250 --> 00:29:20.900
Or a sketchbook,
amazingly, from Auschwitz.

00:29:20.900 --> 00:29:23.340
Found in a bottle in 1947.

00:29:23.340 --> 00:29:25.440
We don't have photographs from Auschwitz.

00:29:25.440 --> 00:29:28.670
We have these sketches, we
don't know who made them.

00:29:28.670 --> 00:29:30.720
We'd have no idea, they're not signed.

00:29:30.720 --> 00:29:34.970
And yet, they bear witness
to people being exterminated

00:29:34.970 --> 00:29:37.563
almost in a photographic-like way.

00:29:40.900 --> 00:29:43.800
I'm haunted to think more, as
I think about this question,

00:29:43.800 --> 00:29:45.980
I've been thinking a
lot more comparatively

00:29:45.980 --> 00:29:48.620
beyond my field of Holocaust
and genocide studies,

00:29:48.620 --> 00:29:51.020
and begin to think about
what messages in bottles

00:29:51.020 --> 00:29:51.853
have never been found?

00:29:51.853 --> 00:29:54.130
What about that other milk
crate that was also buried

00:29:54.130 --> 00:29:55.360
in the Warsaw ghetto?

00:29:55.360 --> 00:29:56.210
It's never been found.

00:29:56.210 --> 00:29:57.310
We don't know where it is.

00:29:57.310 --> 00:30:00.270
What messages and what
knowledge, what witnesses,

00:30:00.270 --> 00:30:02.463
what lives are contained in it?

00:30:03.730 --> 00:30:06.080
Well, think about it this way.

00:30:06.080 --> 00:30:10.453
This is the history of slavery
told through slave ships.

00:30:11.750 --> 00:30:14.407
What you see running there
is an amazing database

00:30:14.407 --> 00:30:17.900
presented by a number of collaborators

00:30:17.900 --> 00:30:21.010
across the world, at Emory University

00:30:21.010 --> 00:30:25.940
detailing slave ships coming
from West Coast of Africa

00:30:25.940 --> 00:30:28.680
to the Americas, to Brazil, to Jamaica,

00:30:28.680 --> 00:30:31.010
to Cuba, to North America.

00:30:31.010 --> 00:30:34.130
It details hundreds of years.

00:30:34.130 --> 00:30:35.900
Each dot is a slave ship.

00:30:35.900 --> 00:30:40.490
Each dot represents somewhere
between 300 and 500 slaves.

00:30:40.490 --> 00:30:42.420
Where are their messages, their voices?

00:30:42.420 --> 00:30:44.320
Who bears witness to them?

00:30:44.320 --> 00:30:48.880
How do we begin to excavate
the submerged knowledge?

00:30:48.880 --> 00:30:51.740
This question, to me,
is a very profound one

00:30:51.740 --> 00:30:54.400
as we begin to think about
the historical record.

00:30:54.400 --> 00:30:57.130
Most of the time what we
have in the historical record

00:30:57.130 --> 00:30:59.820
are the documents of the perpetrators.

00:30:59.820 --> 00:31:03.250
We have the documents
of the legal decisions

00:31:03.250 --> 00:31:05.010
about particular things that happened.

00:31:05.010 --> 00:31:07.370
We have the charters of the ships,

00:31:07.370 --> 00:31:11.510
we have the records of
how many slaves were taken

00:31:11.510 --> 00:31:14.470
how many died in the Middle
Passage and how many arrived

00:31:14.470 --> 00:31:15.650
and where they were enslaved.

00:31:15.650 --> 00:31:18.230
We have their ages, we have their gender.

00:31:18.230 --> 00:31:20.230
We often don't even have their names.

00:31:20.230 --> 00:31:24.140
This particular report is very important

00:31:24.140 --> 00:31:27.130
because it's the Zong slave ship

00:31:27.130 --> 00:31:31.820
which, the owners of the ship,
in the course of the journey

00:31:31.820 --> 00:31:34.540
threw overboard 150 slaves

00:31:34.540 --> 00:31:38.380
and then decided that
they had lost their cargo

00:31:38.380 --> 00:31:41.660
and made a claim against their
insurers to be compensated.

00:31:41.660 --> 00:31:44.380
The only record of this
is the historical record

00:31:44.380 --> 00:31:47.860
the legal documents that
was produced in this debate.

00:31:47.860 --> 00:31:49.330
We know nothing of the people.

00:31:49.330 --> 00:31:52.253
Again, submerged voices,
submerged witnesses.

00:31:53.160 --> 00:31:56.320
Toni Morrison, I think, is
someone who begins to think

00:31:56.320 --> 00:31:59.610
about how literary and historical
knowledge can go together.

00:31:59.610 --> 00:32:01.960
And one thinks about the
millions of people that she says,

00:32:01.960 --> 00:32:03.220
disappear without a trace

00:32:03.220 --> 00:32:05.590
because they never arrive safely onshore.

00:32:05.590 --> 00:32:08.770
It's like a whole nation
that's under the sea.

00:32:08.770 --> 00:32:11.610
Her approach is to think
about literary knowledge.

00:32:11.610 --> 00:32:15.000
How does literary knowledge
complement historical knowledge?

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:18.430
How can literature, poetic thinking,

00:32:18.430 --> 00:32:20.500
and ways of looking at the archive

00:32:20.500 --> 00:32:22.300
bring a truth or shed a light

00:32:22.300 --> 00:32:25.180
on people that were
destroyed, who have no voices?

00:32:25.180 --> 00:32:26.850
Who had no archive?

00:32:26.850 --> 00:32:30.073
She says only an act of the
imagination can help me.

00:32:32.320 --> 00:32:34.710
Her idea of only an
act of the imagination,

00:32:34.710 --> 00:32:38.320
this is not fictionalizing
in the sense of making it up.

00:32:38.320 --> 00:32:40.070
But of adding to the historical record

00:32:40.070 --> 00:32:43.163
in order to show the
silences that exist there.

00:32:44.120 --> 00:32:47.540
My last example is a poet who makes use

00:32:47.540 --> 00:32:51.190
particularly of the Zong
case, NourbeSe Philip.

00:32:51.190 --> 00:32:55.040
Extraordinary book of
poems that came out in 2007

00:32:55.040 --> 00:32:57.760
where she takes that legal
report that I showed you earlier

00:32:57.760 --> 00:33:00.750
this report, here, and
takes apart the words

00:33:00.750 --> 00:33:04.360
pries apart the language
in order to look for

00:33:04.360 --> 00:33:07.460
not only the ways in which
language is connected to power

00:33:07.460 --> 00:33:10.550
but also those voices, the
people that have been left out.

00:33:10.550 --> 00:33:12.650
She says in here, it's
really quite amazing,

00:33:12.650 --> 00:33:13.773
it's a reference.

00:33:15.100 --> 00:33:18.710
Our fellow creatures may
become the subject of property.

00:33:18.710 --> 00:33:21.690
This, therefore, was a
throwing overboard of goods

00:33:21.690 --> 00:33:23.670
and part of it was to save the residue.

00:33:23.670 --> 00:33:25.690
Why they threw the slaves overboard.

00:33:25.690 --> 00:33:28.180
They were essentially goods, like wood

00:33:28.180 --> 00:33:30.040
is what that report says.

00:33:30.040 --> 00:33:32.360
She takes these words and rewrites them.

00:33:32.360 --> 00:33:34.230
She takes them, they kind of are submerged

00:33:34.230 --> 00:33:36.570
some of them come forward,
some come backwards,

00:33:36.570 --> 00:33:38.390
some of them are rewritten.

00:33:38.390 --> 00:33:42.220
But in every case, it's
to bring poetic knowledge

00:33:42.220 --> 00:33:46.010
to show the absences in
the historical record.

00:33:46.010 --> 00:33:48.260
I'll leave you with a
quote from NourbeSe Philip

00:33:48.260 --> 00:33:50.000
because I think it's so telling.

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:51.580
There's no telling the story.

00:33:51.580 --> 00:33:53.850
In fact, the story can't be recovered.

00:33:53.850 --> 00:33:55.220
But it must be told.

00:33:55.220 --> 00:33:56.860
There's paradox, right, there's tension

00:33:56.860 --> 00:33:59.100
of it can't be told, it must be told.

00:33:59.100 --> 00:34:02.240
Zong, her book about this
slave ship, bears witness

00:34:02.240 --> 00:34:04.740
to the resurfacing of the
drowned and the oppressed.

00:34:04.740 --> 00:34:07.220
Transform this desiccated, legal report

00:34:07.220 --> 00:34:11.770
into a cacophony of voices,
wails, cries, moans and shouts

00:34:11.770 --> 00:34:14.290
that had earlier been
banned from the text.

00:34:14.290 --> 00:34:17.234
This, I think, is really the
ethical stakes of knowledge.

00:34:17.234 --> 00:34:18.611
Thank you.

00:34:18.611 --> 00:34:20.556
(audience applauds)

00:34:20.556 --> 00:34:22.417
- Thanks, Todd.

00:34:22.417 --> 00:34:23.750
Thank you, Todd.

00:34:28.036 --> 00:34:30.420
Thanks so much, everybody,
Marcelo Suarez-Orozco.

00:34:30.420 --> 00:34:32.213
- Thank you so much, thank you.

00:34:33.620 --> 00:34:35.880
Thank you, Brett for inviting me

00:34:35.880 --> 00:34:40.880
and thank you to my
colleagues here at the stage

00:34:42.030 --> 00:34:44.640
and my colleagues in the audience

00:34:44.640 --> 00:34:48.563
and I look forward really
more to the conversation.

00:34:49.550 --> 00:34:52.950
I have a few reflections

00:34:52.950 --> 00:34:57.933
that flow from the work of our colleagues.

00:34:59.462 --> 00:35:02.723
I just wanna enumerate them in order.

00:35:03.750 --> 00:35:07.400
Brett, you started us with knowledge

00:35:07.400 --> 00:35:10.253
and its unique attributes.

00:35:11.468 --> 00:35:13.280
I was thinking as you were speaking

00:35:13.280 --> 00:35:18.280
that perhaps what is uniquely
human is the accumulation

00:35:18.980 --> 00:35:23.673
and the accumulated
transmission of knowledge

00:35:25.570 --> 00:35:29.113
as perhaps one of the
uniquely human attributes.

00:35:30.070 --> 00:35:31.320
We don't have to reinvent

00:35:33.140 --> 00:35:36.043
the grammar of the French language.

00:35:37.190 --> 00:35:38.860
Once it's articulated

00:35:38.860 --> 00:35:43.860
it has a life that is transgenerational.

00:35:44.010 --> 00:35:46.720
So the accumulation of knowledge,

00:35:46.720 --> 00:35:50.970
we'll get to the question of what that is,

00:35:50.970 --> 00:35:55.480
may be a uniquely human attribute.

00:35:55.480 --> 00:35:58.150
I think perhaps another
uniquely human capacity

00:35:58.150 --> 00:36:01.530
I was reflecting upon
your comments, Brett,

00:36:01.530 --> 00:36:06.380
had to do with your reflection on

00:36:06.380 --> 00:36:10.670
how do we know that we know something?

00:36:10.670 --> 00:36:12.760
And that of course speaks to something

00:36:12.760 --> 00:36:17.760
that may be the jewel in crown.

00:36:18.870 --> 00:36:23.870
What cognitive neuroscientists
call the metacognitive.

00:36:26.020 --> 00:36:29.310
The so-called executive function

00:36:29.310 --> 00:36:31.740
of the central nervous system.

00:36:31.740 --> 00:36:36.740
This, again, may be uniquely
human capacity to reflect upon

00:36:38.520 --> 00:36:39.880
our knowing.

00:36:39.880 --> 00:36:43.473
The so-called metacognitive architecture

00:36:45.370 --> 00:36:50.370
that is so much a part of
who we are as a species.

00:36:55.840 --> 00:37:00.840
Victoria, your work with
the body, it's so amazing.

00:37:00.890 --> 00:37:03.040
And of course, the body knows.

00:37:03.040 --> 00:37:07.040
Pascal has a beautiful line when he says,

00:37:07.040 --> 00:37:11.100
and I think he means more
broadly, he has a line,

00:37:11.100 --> 00:37:16.100
the heart knows a reason for
which reason has no reason.

00:37:17.500 --> 00:37:22.500
There are ways the body
knows that our other that

00:37:24.441 --> 00:37:29.441
the binary logic of the
Cartesian sort-of world

00:37:30.950 --> 00:37:35.690
of mind and body, culture, nature.

00:37:35.690 --> 00:37:40.690
So, I applaud you for reminding us

00:37:41.940 --> 00:37:46.940
how much of the human
experience and human evolution

00:37:47.170 --> 00:37:50.110
is the work the body does

00:37:52.515 --> 00:37:55.993
in terms of our orientation to the world.

00:37:58.370 --> 00:38:03.370
Todd, of course, I was very
moved by your reflections

00:38:03.570 --> 00:38:08.220
and this, I think, is why acknowledgement

00:38:08.220 --> 00:38:10.210
and the politics of acknowledgement

00:38:11.060 --> 00:38:15.710
becomes so central to the endeavors

00:38:15.710 --> 00:38:18.380
to heal the extraordinary damage

00:38:18.380 --> 00:38:21.240
human beings can do to each other.

00:38:21.240 --> 00:38:25.590
And think of the Truth and
Reconciliation committees

00:38:25.590 --> 00:38:28.520
in South Africa, in Latin America,

00:38:28.520 --> 00:38:32.298
in so many parts of the
world, where, of course.

00:38:32.298 --> 00:38:34.622
Elaine Scarry has a beautiful line

00:38:34.622 --> 00:38:38.000
in her book The Body in Pain on torture.

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:39.220
She says, of course, in torture,

00:38:39.220 --> 00:38:41.120
the pain can't be represented.

00:38:41.120 --> 00:38:43.670
We don't have language, it is unknowable,

00:38:43.670 --> 00:38:44.620
the pain of others.

00:38:45.776 --> 00:38:47.160
Not unlike what Adorno said

00:38:47.160 --> 00:38:50.663
about the truth is buried in the ashes.

00:38:51.540 --> 00:38:54.820
We can endeavor to excavate
it but it's a very incomplete

00:38:54.820 --> 00:38:56.840
and very imperfect.

00:38:56.840 --> 00:39:01.140
So knowledge and
acknowledgement are so central

00:39:01.140 --> 00:39:05.260
to the work of suffering
in the human condition.

00:39:08.500 --> 00:39:11.290
So these are some
reflections to my comments

00:39:11.290 --> 00:39:15.310
to my colleagues in the
spirit of conversation.

00:39:15.310 --> 00:39:16.643
So, knowledge, knowledge, how do we know?

00:39:18.033 --> 00:39:20.330
I'll start, wear my hat here

00:39:20.330 --> 00:39:21.610
as the Dean of the Graduate School

00:39:21.610 --> 00:39:25.590
of Education and
Information Studies at UCLA

00:39:25.590 --> 00:39:28.200
and I'll start with the following claim

00:39:28.200 --> 00:39:31.760
that knowledge is dangerous
and proceed with caution

00:39:31.760 --> 00:39:33.520
when you're dealing with knowledge.

00:39:33.520 --> 00:39:35.660
But let me make this claim.

00:39:35.660 --> 00:39:39.990
It is a fundamental pillar of,

00:39:39.990 --> 00:39:42.580
let's put it very broadly, civilization.

00:39:42.580 --> 00:39:46.330
The great H. G. Wells, 150 years ago, said

00:39:46.330 --> 00:39:51.330
history now is a race between
education and catastrophe.

00:39:52.440 --> 00:39:54.730
Well, if you know something,

00:39:54.730 --> 00:39:58.080
you know who's winning that race today.

00:39:58.080 --> 00:39:59.730
(audience laughs)

00:39:59.730 --> 00:40:03.240
Knowledge is a fundamental pillar

00:40:03.240 --> 00:40:05.303
of democracy, of civilization.

00:40:05.303 --> 00:40:07.770
This is why the great John Dewey,

00:40:07.770 --> 00:40:10.540
in his book Democracy and Education,

00:40:10.540 --> 00:40:14.570
puts education, puts the knowing citizen

00:40:16.240 --> 00:40:18.920
at the center of the work of democracy.

00:40:18.920 --> 00:40:23.920
And prophetically, Dewey
says, the work of democracy

00:40:23.980 --> 00:40:28.600
is the work that each
generation needs to renew.

00:40:28.600 --> 00:40:33.600
And it's renewed through,
in his wisdom, education.

00:40:35.830 --> 00:40:38.780
His main argument is education is not

00:40:38.780 --> 00:40:40.310
a preparation for life.

00:40:40.310 --> 00:40:43.210
Education is life, and democracy lives

00:40:43.210 --> 00:40:46.010
in the work education does for all of us.

00:40:46.010 --> 00:40:50.420
So this is sort of the first
broad claim about knowledge.

00:40:50.420 --> 00:40:55.420
A pillar for, especially,
again, as Brett got us started,

00:40:57.990 --> 00:41:02.990
in the current world where
knowledge and facts and reality

00:41:07.291 --> 00:41:11.410
are contested in the most
savage, sort of fundamental ways

00:41:11.410 --> 00:41:14.140
where language is kidnapped from us

00:41:14.140 --> 00:41:17.410
and all the shared understandings
that are fundamental

00:41:17.410 --> 00:41:21.567
to the work of knowledge are ephemeral.

00:41:24.150 --> 00:41:26.470
Now, more formally, when
we think about knowledge

00:41:26.470 --> 00:41:28.120
of course, and this is something

00:41:28.120 --> 00:41:33.120
that Victoria articulated
for us, we think in terms of

00:41:36.312 --> 00:41:41.312
knowledge is cognition, knowledge.

00:41:43.593 --> 00:41:45.550
(speaking in foreign language)

00:41:45.550 --> 00:41:48.200
These are all cognate words.

00:41:48.200 --> 00:41:50.000
And they flow from two separate

00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:53.670
sort of very basic constitutive units.

00:41:53.670 --> 00:41:57.710
One is experience and familiarity.

00:41:57.710 --> 00:42:02.283
The habits that the body knows
often better than the mind.

00:42:03.940 --> 00:42:06.450
This is what the great William James

00:42:06.450 --> 00:42:10.440
called experience near knowledge.

00:42:10.440 --> 00:42:13.890
The knowledge that comes from the habit.

00:42:13.890 --> 00:42:17.870
Knowledge is a cognate
word of familiarity also.

00:42:17.870 --> 00:42:22.340
Is that which comes to
us as a way of knowing

00:42:22.340 --> 00:42:26.320
that is familiar, that
we are at ease with.

00:42:26.320 --> 00:42:29.420
So that's one of the ways

00:42:29.420 --> 00:42:34.327
of entering an approach to knowledge.

00:42:36.240 --> 00:42:39.363
What I think you called natural knowing.

00:42:40.800 --> 00:42:42.837
Of course, we are in the university,

00:42:42.837 --> 00:42:47.360
and the university is in the
business of what we will call

00:42:47.360 --> 00:42:50.260
ways of knowing that are organized

00:42:50.260 --> 00:42:53.680
and they tend to be organized
into the disciplines.

00:42:53.680 --> 00:42:58.680
We had a brilliant discussion by Todd

00:43:00.710 --> 00:43:05.600
that very much flows from the architecture

00:43:05.600 --> 00:43:08.400
of a set of disciplinary understandings

00:43:08.400 --> 00:43:11.032
that are shared, they're common,

00:43:11.032 --> 00:43:13.000
they're habits that we form.

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:17.800
And in a university,
knowledge tends to live

00:43:17.800 --> 00:43:20.923
in disciplinary habitats.

00:43:22.360 --> 00:43:25.760
We have historical ways of knowing.

00:43:25.760 --> 00:43:28.403
Geographical ways of knowing.

00:43:29.290 --> 00:43:31.810
Philosophical ways of knowing.

00:43:31.810 --> 00:43:36.180
Architectural ways of
knowing, and the like.

00:43:37.220 --> 00:43:39.930
Immediately, something very
fascinating begins to happen

00:43:39.930 --> 00:43:44.670
which is, there is a reason why
knowledge over the centuries

00:43:44.670 --> 00:43:47.510
became organized around systems

00:43:47.510 --> 00:43:49.670
that we come to call disciplines.

00:43:49.670 --> 00:43:52.250
And that is, what happens

00:43:52.250 --> 00:43:56.483
where the disciplines come to converse?

00:43:59.370 --> 00:44:03.353
What happens when, before
I joined the dark side

00:44:07.230 --> 00:44:11.160
and I became an administrator,
I was a regular academic.

00:44:11.160 --> 00:44:14.160
I was a regular scholar
who did regular research

00:44:14.160 --> 00:44:17.630
and wrote regular books and articles.

