that's very much not top-down or driven

01:15:51.090 --> 01:15:52.790
by that kind of master model

01:15:52.790 --> 01:15:55.320
which is there in the history of pedagogy.

01:15:55.320 --> 01:15:58.640
Even the term pedagogue is
a master who led children.

01:15:58.640 --> 01:16:00.040
That was where it came from.

01:16:00.040 --> 01:16:02.870
This of course changed over
time, and thankfully so.

01:16:02.870 --> 01:16:05.490
But it had a sense of
hierarchical, you know,

01:16:05.490 --> 01:16:08.110
you had knowledge, it was passed down.

01:16:08.110 --> 01:16:08.943
Pedagogy of the Oppressed

01:16:08.943 --> 01:16:11.130
was really inverting that
in very fundamental ways

01:16:11.130 --> 01:16:14.350
and creating a much broader
community of practitioners

01:16:14.350 --> 01:16:18.000
and participants in a
kind of dialogical, open

01:16:18.000 --> 01:16:20.230
and obviously dialectically inflected way.

01:16:20.230 --> 01:16:22.400
He's very much inflected
by Hegel and Marx.

01:16:22.400 --> 01:16:25.010
And that was the basic of the critique

01:16:25.010 --> 01:16:27.610
which again brings in
the critique of capital

01:16:27.610 --> 01:16:29.247
and the critique of capitalism

01:16:29.247 --> 01:16:33.700
and those who have and
wield power in various ways.

01:16:33.700 --> 01:16:37.168
So I think this is an avenue,
to me, that we wanna reclaim,

01:16:37.168 --> 01:16:39.530
That we really wanna prioritize

01:16:39.530 --> 01:16:42.320
when we think about
education is that tradition

01:16:42.320 --> 01:16:44.960
that I think Freire and really going back

01:16:44.960 --> 01:16:49.020
probably to Marx also
really brought to the fore.

01:16:49.020 --> 01:16:50.740
The other thing I wanted to respond to.

01:16:50.740 --> 01:16:52.330
The German tradition is interesting, too,

01:16:52.330 --> 01:16:54.834
because the word for education there is.

01:16:54.834 --> 01:16:56.600
(speaks in foreign language)

01:16:56.600 --> 01:16:57.950
It comes from sculpture,

01:16:57.950 --> 01:17:00.210
which means you can turn,
you can make something.

01:17:00.210 --> 01:17:01.757
It also has a sense of image.

01:17:01.757 --> 01:17:04.040
You can be like in the image of God,

01:17:04.040 --> 01:17:05.610
because that was one
way to think about it.

01:17:05.610 --> 01:17:08.960
But it was also a sense of
formation or creation or making.

01:17:08.960 --> 01:17:11.540
But you really have a sense
of artistic practice there

01:17:11.540 --> 01:17:12.850
and it's very much open-ended.

01:17:12.850 --> 01:17:16.070
It didn't necessarily lead
in one particular direction.

01:17:16.070 --> 01:17:17.790
And when the German universities

01:17:17.790 --> 01:17:20.300
in the early 19th century were founded,

01:17:20.300 --> 01:17:22.570
I'm kind of thinking in
terms of Humboldt and others

01:17:22.570 --> 01:17:25.260
and this idea of liberal education.

01:17:25.260 --> 01:17:27.030
This became important
to the United States.

01:17:27.030 --> 01:17:28.830
This was really a tradition that was

01:17:28.830 --> 01:17:33.170
of the multi-sided education
of the human being.

01:17:33.170 --> 01:17:35.670
Disciplines were not meant to be silos

01:17:35.670 --> 01:17:36.720
but were meant to be traversed.

01:17:36.720 --> 01:17:39.010
And education was really holistic.

01:17:39.010 --> 01:17:43.350
It was about thinking about
the human being as a whole.

01:17:43.350 --> 01:17:47.400
So, to be educated is also to be formed

01:17:47.400 --> 01:17:50.283
and form is never teleological.

01:17:51.765 --> 01:17:53.963
- The other inversion, Todd, is of course

01:17:53.963 --> 01:17:58.963
Maria Montessori and Christina
Rinaldi of Reggio Children

01:17:59.000 --> 01:18:04.000
where the child is the point of entry

01:18:05.240 --> 01:18:06.990
into teaching and learning.

01:18:06.990 --> 01:18:09.180
It's who's teaching whom.
- Exactly.

01:18:09.180 --> 01:18:11.760
- We were in Erice recently, in Sicily.

01:18:11.760 --> 01:18:16.760
And Christina Rinaldi, who
is runs the Reggio Children,

01:18:17.010 --> 01:18:20.900
these are the best preschools in the world

01:18:20.900 --> 01:18:25.861
starts with, so who is
teaching who here? (chuckles)

01:18:25.861 --> 01:18:30.861
And of course, Montessori,
Rinaldi, so many others

01:18:31.330 --> 01:18:33.270
the moment you put the child

01:18:33.270 --> 01:18:36.520
at the center of teaching and learning

01:18:36.520 --> 01:18:39.070
you have a radically different idea

01:18:39.070 --> 01:18:44.070
that inverts this hierarchical
story that we know so well

01:18:51.770 --> 01:18:53.300
in education.

01:18:53.300 --> 01:18:55.120
- I'm gonna open the
conversation to the floor

01:18:55.120 --> 01:18:55.953
in just a moment.

01:18:55.953 --> 01:18:57.680
As a transition to that, one
thing I'm really struck by

01:18:57.680 --> 01:18:58.790
across the four presentations

01:18:58.790 --> 01:19:03.310
is that a sense of responsibility
brought very close to bear

01:19:03.310 --> 01:19:05.510
on any idea of knowledge
that we might contemplate.

01:19:05.510 --> 01:19:07.860
And I guess an obvious
question for each of you

01:19:09.600 --> 01:19:13.060
or any of you that might want
to take a stab at it would be

01:19:13.060 --> 01:19:16.350
who do you feel most responsible to

01:19:16.350 --> 01:19:20.160
in thinking about your own work
and thinking and performance

01:19:20.160 --> 01:19:25.160
or scholarship or participation
as a producer, understander,

01:19:27.400 --> 01:19:29.500
communicator of knowledge today?

01:19:29.500 --> 01:19:31.990
Where does the responsibility
lie in your own thinking

01:19:31.990 --> 01:19:33.273
in the work you do?

01:19:35.100 --> 01:19:37.110
Is it to your peers, is
it to your audiences?

01:19:37.110 --> 01:19:42.110
Is it to yourself, is it to
a larger category of being?

01:19:46.960 --> 01:19:48.413
- Okay, I'll give it a try.

01:19:51.030 --> 01:19:52.980
I couldn't say that there would be one.

01:19:54.110 --> 01:19:56.120
I think that there are constantly

01:19:56.120 --> 01:19:59.010
multiple spheres of responsibility.

01:19:59.010 --> 01:20:03.080
Of course, I don't feel
responsible to myself

01:20:03.080 --> 01:20:08.080
I simply feel passionately
engaged with learning more.

01:20:09.520 --> 01:20:13.380
I feel responsible to all
the people who work with me

01:20:13.380 --> 01:20:16.520
in the process of creating something.

01:20:16.520 --> 01:20:20.390
In fact, that process sometimes becomes

01:20:20.390 --> 01:20:22.190
the most important thing.

01:20:22.190 --> 01:20:25.470
And I feel fascinated by the
process and responsibility

01:20:25.470 --> 01:20:28.390
of what happens to this thing that I make

01:20:28.390 --> 01:20:33.390
when it enters the world,
when it becomes something

01:20:33.920 --> 01:20:38.653
that for a few moments
can be engaged by others.

01:20:40.330 --> 01:20:41.756
That's my try.

01:20:41.756 --> 01:20:42.870
- And it's a responsibility.

01:20:42.870 --> 01:20:45.500
What I find most gratifying
is, I write about immigration,

01:20:45.500 --> 01:20:49.870
when I give a talk and a young
person comes and tells me

01:20:49.870 --> 01:20:53.440
yes, this speaks authentically
to my experience.

01:20:53.440 --> 01:20:57.740
I feel that is maybe the
most gratifying space

01:20:57.740 --> 01:21:02.740
for me to be in, when
somebody, a young person often,

01:21:03.030 --> 01:21:07.080
says, you know, this tells my story.

01:21:07.080 --> 01:21:08.730
To me, there's nothing greater

01:21:08.730 --> 01:21:13.730
than that faithful
representation of the voices,

01:21:14.390 --> 01:21:18.960
the dreams, the ambitions, the anxieties

01:21:18.960 --> 01:21:20.900
of people that teach me.

01:21:20.900 --> 01:21:23.010
Remember, I'm an anthropologist.

01:21:23.010 --> 01:21:25.310
And in anthropology,
the only right you have

01:21:25.310 --> 01:21:27.930
is the right to be
ignorant about the people.

01:21:27.930 --> 01:21:29.662
As the great Cliff Geertz said,

01:21:29.662 --> 01:21:31.750
knowledge is local knowledge.

01:21:31.750 --> 01:21:36.750
It lives with your colleagues
and the endeavor becomes

01:21:36.790 --> 01:21:39.180
constructing a set of understanding

01:21:39.180 --> 01:21:44.180
that is faithful to the
experience of your collaborators.

01:21:48.630 --> 01:21:52.690
- It's a question I
wrestle with constantly.

01:21:52.690 --> 01:21:56.490
And I feel that there's
an ethical dimension

01:21:56.490 --> 01:22:00.070
in the work that I try to do

01:22:00.070 --> 01:22:02.860
and I also am conscious of my failures

01:22:02.860 --> 01:22:06.420
to be able to take on that responsibility.

01:22:06.420 --> 01:22:08.800
And I mean that by, I have a voice

01:22:08.800 --> 01:22:11.700
and I have a certain amount of
privilege that comes with it.

01:22:11.700 --> 01:22:15.410
In various domains,
whether it's being male

01:22:15.410 --> 01:22:18.100
or able-bodied, Caucasian.

01:22:18.100 --> 01:22:20.540
And I think that there's an obligation

01:22:20.540 --> 01:22:24.620
to understand and be
critical of that privilege

01:22:24.620 --> 01:22:27.780
but also what it means to stand open

01:22:29.320 --> 01:22:32.850
and be willing to listen to voices

01:22:32.850 --> 01:22:36.560
that don't have the same
opportunities for amplification.

01:22:36.560 --> 01:22:38.863
And that's where the
responsibility comes from

01:22:38.863 --> 01:22:40.920
when I'm thinking about the archive

01:22:40.920 --> 01:22:43.870
or these voices that I was mentioning.

01:22:43.870 --> 01:22:47.310
You become kind of a
steward for knowledge.

01:22:47.310 --> 01:22:49.380
A possible conduit,

01:22:49.380 --> 01:22:52.120
but also one who can refract
it in different ways.

01:22:52.120 --> 01:22:54.600
But knowing that you're also extremely,

01:22:54.600 --> 01:22:57.030
it's a very precarious position.

01:22:57.030 --> 01:23:01.548
And you have to ask yourself,
I ask myself constantly

01:23:01.548 --> 01:23:03.870
what responsibility comes with that.

01:23:03.870 --> 01:23:05.640
- [Brett] Thank you.

01:23:05.640 --> 01:23:06.903
- Yeah, I love that.

01:23:08.540 --> 01:23:13.540
For me, similarly,
responsibility, privilege

01:23:16.190 --> 01:23:18.000
all these different kinds of things.

01:23:18.000 --> 01:23:19.270
I can look it on the one hand

01:23:19.270 --> 01:23:21.100
as a human being walking
around in the world

01:23:21.100 --> 01:23:26.100
and I can say that, you
know, my kids, my mother.

01:23:28.650 --> 01:23:32.350
My mother died this summer,
my kids are in growth.

01:23:32.350 --> 01:23:35.760
The bodies of knowledge that
I have did not prepare me

01:23:35.760 --> 01:23:37.460
for either of those things.

01:23:37.460 --> 01:23:42.460
And yet somehow I am able
to draw from something

01:23:43.330 --> 01:23:46.400
that came to me from
somewhere, et cetera, et cetera

01:23:46.400 --> 01:23:49.290
to navigate those points
where you do have to flip

01:23:49.290 --> 01:23:52.810
towards wisdom and rely
deeply on ignorance.

01:23:52.810 --> 01:23:55.210
And the lack of knowing in a blind way

01:23:55.210 --> 01:23:58.960
doesn't absolve you of
responsibility to care.

01:23:58.960 --> 01:24:00.440
So I think of it in that term.

01:24:00.440 --> 01:24:02.200
When I think of it territorially speaking

01:24:02.200 --> 01:24:03.440
which is a similar kind of thing.

01:24:03.440 --> 01:24:08.440
From Freire, to care enough,
to care for the thing.

01:24:09.260 --> 01:24:12.460
And that is a job description
in my humble opinion.

01:24:12.460 --> 01:24:14.790
The rest are just are just
acronyms and business cards

01:24:14.790 --> 01:24:17.210
and things, but that's a job description.

01:24:17.210 --> 01:24:18.230
When I think of it, I think of it

01:24:18.230 --> 01:24:21.140
through the eyes, often,
of a theater director,

01:24:21.140 --> 01:24:25.160
a profound theater
director, Ariane Mnouchkine

01:24:25.160 --> 01:24:27.100
She's based outside of Paris.

01:24:27.100 --> 01:24:30.520
I asked her one time how
she prepares the cast

01:24:30.520 --> 01:24:34.150
to perform the work for
like the 300th, 400th time

01:24:34.150 --> 01:24:36.620
with such intensity, because
of the subject matter

01:24:36.620 --> 01:24:38.770
that they deal with often in the work.

01:24:38.770 --> 01:24:41.000
And they get together beforehand

01:24:41.000 --> 01:24:44.440
and stand in a kind of
huddle and she says to them

01:24:45.400 --> 01:24:48.020
tonight there will be
someone in the theater

01:24:48.020 --> 01:24:52.083
who has never been here,
we perform for that person.

01:24:53.540 --> 01:24:55.730
Tonight is also a person
that will be the last time

01:24:55.730 --> 01:24:58.713
they're in a theater, we
perform for that person.

01:25:00.310 --> 01:25:04.863
My sense of responsibility is
the belief in that potential.

01:25:06.720 --> 01:25:08.670
- Terrific, thank you, amazing you all.

01:25:09.640 --> 01:25:11.250
Let's turn it and open
it up to the floor here.

01:25:11.250 --> 01:25:12.890
I've got, just to start.

01:25:12.890 --> 01:25:14.930
Our TAs have got microphones
with some of the students,

01:25:14.930 --> 01:25:15.763
let's begin there.

01:25:15.763 --> 01:25:18.110
Kyle, you've got someone
here, yeah, please.

01:25:18.110 --> 01:25:21.910
- Hello, thank you all for
coming tonight and presenting.

01:25:21.910 --> 01:25:24.320
All the presentations were amazing.

01:25:24.320 --> 01:25:27.500
My question is, how do
instructors or institutions

01:25:27.500 --> 01:25:30.110
determine what is better
for students to learn

01:25:30.110 --> 01:25:31.770
and what is the process that goes behind

01:25:31.770 --> 01:25:34.253
what knowledge is best
passed to the students?

01:25:36.230 --> 01:25:37.480
And this is for everyone.

01:25:38.660 --> 01:25:40.251
- [Todd] I'm gonna leave
that to the academics.

01:25:40.251 --> 01:25:43.013
(panel chuckles)

01:25:43.013 --> 01:25:45.550
- So as a Dean I would say the following,

01:25:45.550 --> 01:25:48.840
which is this really
lives with the faculty

01:25:48.840 --> 01:25:51.730
and the autonomy of the faculty

01:25:51.730 --> 01:25:54.750
and the faculty's judgment as pertinent

01:25:54.750 --> 01:25:59.750
to the very thoughtful and
thorough question you posed.

01:26:04.780 --> 01:26:08.590
So really, there is a ways in which

01:26:10.960 --> 01:26:13.823
the disciplines organize themselves.

01:26:15.030 --> 01:26:20.030
The individual faculty members
have a great deal of latitude

01:26:20.560 --> 01:26:25.560
as to how to engage in the
endeavor of teaching and learning

01:26:27.290 --> 01:26:30.873
and the working with students.

01:26:31.910 --> 01:26:33.760
So there's a great deal of autonomy.

01:26:33.760 --> 01:26:38.760
While, I think, the disciplines
hold a very important space

01:26:40.130 --> 01:26:45.117
in how teaching and
learning are organized,

01:26:46.460 --> 01:26:48.920
ultimately, faculty members

01:26:50.180 --> 01:26:53.940
really have the autonomy and the range

01:26:53.940 --> 01:26:58.940
to actualize those general
principles in the classroom.

01:27:02.120 --> 01:27:06.120
- I think when I decide

01:27:06.120 --> 01:27:07.800
what knowledge should be passed forward,

01:27:07.800 --> 01:27:09.450
like to say, when I put
a syllabus together,

01:27:09.450 --> 01:27:11.197
I made some decisions as
to what we're gonna read

01:27:11.197 --> 01:27:12.760
and what we're not gonna read

01:27:12.760 --> 01:27:15.560
and what we're gonna watch
or not watch, if it's a film.

01:27:16.440 --> 01:27:20.833
And those decisions are always,

01:27:21.863 --> 01:27:23.763
you question them constantly.

01:27:25.060 --> 01:27:27.290
It's not that you do this one time.

01:27:27.290 --> 01:27:29.310
It's constantly asking
yourself what knowledge

01:27:29.310 --> 01:27:32.680
should be practiced or passed forward.

01:27:32.680 --> 01:27:37.680
For me, I'm interested in texts
or documents that will haunt

01:27:39.210 --> 01:27:42.220
that will stay with you as you grow

01:27:42.220 --> 01:27:44.440
and that you'll come
back to in different ways

01:27:44.440 --> 01:27:47.620
because they mean things,
perhaps differently,

01:27:47.620 --> 01:27:51.300
as you encounter them at
different points in your life.

01:27:51.300 --> 01:27:53.973
And I often select things
that that's happened to me.

01:27:54.849 --> 01:27:56.870
So I may have read something when I was 20

01:27:56.870 --> 01:27:59.170
and when I'm 40, I'm gonna
read it quite differently

01:27:59.170 --> 01:28:02.210
and I imagine when I'm 60
I'll read it again differently

01:28:02.210 --> 01:28:05.400
and that's actually part of the point

01:28:05.400 --> 01:28:09.150
because it speaks of the process of growth

01:28:09.150 --> 01:28:12.130
that I go through and
that you will go through.

01:28:12.130 --> 01:28:14.246
Nothing is static.

01:28:14.246 --> 01:28:17.060
Who you are is constantly
changing and evolving.

01:28:17.060 --> 01:28:18.600
The language you're using.

01:28:18.600 --> 01:28:20.010
I don't mean just the
language you're speaking

01:28:20.010 --> 01:28:20.930
although I do mean that.

01:28:20.930 --> 01:28:23.300
But I also mean the expressiveness

01:28:23.300 --> 01:28:27.890
and the way we encounter a text.

01:28:27.890 --> 01:28:29.390
And it doesn't have to
be written, of course.

01:28:29.390 --> 01:28:30.543
It can be performed.

01:28:31.810 --> 01:28:32.780
These things all change.

01:28:32.780 --> 01:28:35.970
And so I'm interested
that'll haunt us though

01:28:35.970 --> 01:28:38.753
and in things that we'll have
to reckon with more than once.

01:28:39.860 --> 01:28:40.693
- Thank you.

01:28:41.810 --> 01:28:43.560
Over on this side, Gigi or Anna,

01:28:43.560 --> 01:28:44.830
do we have someone on that side?

01:28:44.830 --> 01:28:46.213
- There's someone right there.

01:28:47.230 --> 01:28:50.230
- Where, I'm sorry, I'm looking,
oh yes, right here, please.

01:28:54.300 --> 01:28:57.330
- It's on.
- Sorry, okay.

01:28:57.330 --> 01:28:59.410
Hi and thank you all again.

01:28:59.410 --> 01:29:02.240
My question is, if knowledge
is as valuable and scarce

01:29:02.240 --> 01:29:03.540
as we've been taught,

01:29:03.540 --> 01:29:06.350
why does society push
education on everyone?

01:29:06.350 --> 01:29:08.950
Wouldn't that take away from
the quality of knowledge itself

01:29:08.950 --> 01:29:11.730
or is it that we're only
subject to limited truths

01:29:11.730 --> 01:29:14.530
and the full lengths of
information should be protected?

01:29:18.542 --> 01:29:19.542
- Thank you.

01:29:21.220 --> 01:29:25.773
- So, knowledge is imperfect
and it's in perpetual change.

01:29:25.773 --> 01:29:27.640
There's also such thing as progress.

01:29:27.640 --> 01:29:32.480
Meaning the fact that more
people become educated

01:29:32.480 --> 01:29:36.093
and more people are familiar,

01:29:39.630 --> 01:29:42.863
to go back to Victoria's point of entry,

01:29:43.920 --> 01:29:48.920
makes for a more democratic society

01:29:52.200 --> 01:29:57.200
where more voices in the
citizenry can weigh in

01:29:59.240 --> 01:30:03.923
on the issues of the day.

01:30:04.930 --> 01:30:07.325
The pursuit of knowledge
is eternal because

01:30:07.325 --> 01:30:10.863
knowledge is imperfect and incomplete.

01:30:12.629 --> 01:30:16.347
Knowledge is never
extracting truth from facts

01:30:18.090 --> 01:30:20.559
and from nature and from archives.

01:30:20.559 --> 01:30:24.570
It's more like making sausage.
(audience laughs)

01:30:24.570 --> 01:30:27.333
It's not so pretty up close.

01:30:28.690 --> 01:30:33.690
And we make mistakes and we come back.

01:30:34.060 --> 01:30:37.253
We accumulate knowledge.

01:30:38.960 --> 01:30:43.913
We go past previous
traps, previous mistakes.

01:30:45.220 --> 01:30:48.260
So it's a perpetual endeavor, it's never.

01:30:48.260 --> 01:30:49.600
I think, and I told Franz,

01:30:49.600 --> 01:30:53.030
that a work of art is never finished.

01:30:53.030 --> 01:30:54.400
It's abandoned.

01:30:54.400 --> 01:30:55.890
You can say the same about knowledge.

01:30:55.890 --> 01:30:57.970
The pursuit of knowledge
is never finished.

01:30:57.970 --> 01:31:01.637
Some of us abandon it earlier than others.

